  :confidentiality "public"
  :book-version "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Score = base × combo × difficulty. That's the whole idea. This
appendix expands the shortcut into twelve variations, each drawn
from a different arcade genre.

## The base formula

```
score-per-hit = base * combo-multiplier * difficulty * bonus
```

- `base` — points per hit, varies by target
- `combo-multiplier` — starts at 1, grows with successive hits
- `difficulty` — global scale from level/mode
- `bonus` — situational: air kill bonus, perfect-timing bonus, etc.

Every scoring system in every arcade game is this formula with the
knobs turned differently.

## Variation 1 — Classic (Pac-style)

```scheme
;; Ghost worth 200. Chain 4 ghosts in one power-pill: 200/400/800/1600.
(define ghost-chain 0)
(define (eat-ghost)
  (set! ghost-chain (+ ghost-chain 1))
  (set! score (+ score (* 200 (expt 2 (- ghost-chain 1))))))
```

Powers-of-two scaling. First ghost 200, second 400, fourth 1600.
The rush of the fourth-ghost bite is exponential.

## Variation 2 — Shmup (multi-value targets)

```scheme
;; Small enemy 100; medium 300; large 800; boss 5000.
(define target-values
  '((small . 100) (medium . 300) (large . 800) (boss . 5000)))
(define (kill-target kind)
  (set! score (+ score (* (cdr (assq kind target-values)) combo))))
```

Base score varies by target kind. Combo multiplies uniformly.

## Variation 3 — Tetris-style (line-clear scaling)

```scheme
;; 1 line = 40; 2 = 100; 3 = 300; 4 = 1200. Level multiplies.
(define line-values #(0 40 100 300 1200))
(define (clear-lines n)
  (set! score (+ score (* (vector-ref line-values n) (+ level 1)))))
```

Clearing 4 at once is worth much more than 4 clears of 1. Rewards
strategic play.

## Variation 4 — Rhythm (timing-based)

```scheme
;; Perfect: 100. Great: 60. Good: 30. Miss: 0.
;; Combo grows on hits (perfect/great/good); breaks on miss.
(define (rhythm-hit rating)
  (case rating
    ((perfect) (set! combo (+ combo 1))
               (set! score (+ score (* 100 combo))))
    ((great)   (set! combo (+ combo 1))
               (set! score (+ score (* 60 combo))))
    ((good)    (set! combo (+ combo 1))
               (set! score (+ score (* 30 combo))))
    ((miss)    (set! combo 0))))
```

Combo timing precision is rewarded. Perfect chain = high score.

## Variation 5 — Fighter (damage-scaled)

```scheme
;; Damage dealt = base score. Combo counter increments per hit;
;; combo scale caps at 3.0.
(define (deal-damage dmg)
  (set! combo (+ combo 1))
  (set! score (+ score (* dmg (min 3.0 (+ 1 (* combo 0.1)))))))
```

Every hit worth its damage. Combo cap prevents infinite juggle
scoring.

## Variation 6 — Racing (time-inverse)

```scheme
;; Score = base + (max-time - your-time) * 10.
(define (finish-race your-time max-time)
  (set! score (+ 1000 (* (max 0 (- max-time your-time)) 10))))
```

Faster = higher. Base always awarded for finishing.

## Variation 7 — Puzzle (efficiency-scaled)

```scheme
;; Score = base - (moves-used * 10).
(define (solve-puzzle moves-used)
  (set! score (+ score (max 100 (- 1000 (* moves-used 10))))))
```

Fewer moves = higher score. Min score prevents shame-punishment.

## Variation 8 — Shmup with chain grazing

```scheme
;; Killing an enemy: base score. Grazing (near-miss with bullet):
;; small bonus that MULTIPLIES the next kill.
(define graze-count 0)
(define (graze-bullet)
  (set! graze-count (+ graze-count 1))
  (world/camera-shake! 1 0.9))
(define (kill-enemy)
  (set! score (+ score (* 100 (+ 1 graze-count))))
  (set! graze-count 0))
```

Style bonuses. Getting closer to death = more points if you survive.

## Variation 9 — Beat-em-up (crowd multiplier)

```scheme
;; Base + bonus per enemy currently onscreen.
(define (defeat-enemy)
  (let ((crowd (world/count 'enemy)))
    (set! score (+ score (+ 100 (* 20 crowd))))))
```

Being surrounded = worth more per kill. Rewards daring play.

## Variation 10 — Platformer (time + collectibles)

```scheme
;; End-of-level: base + time bonus + collectibles.
(define (end-level time-left coins-collected)
  (set! score (+ score
                 1000                    ;; base
                 (* time-left 10)         ;; time bonus
                 (* coins-collected 50)))) ;; collectible bonus
```

Multiple axes; player can optimize for speed OR collection.

## Variation 11 — Roguelike (streak multiplier)

```scheme
;; Streak grows each run. Dying resets it. Score at end of run =
;; run-score * streak.
(define run-streak 1)
(define (end-run alive?)
  (if alive?
      (begin (set! score (+ score (* run-score run-streak)))
             (set! run-streak (+ run-streak 1)))
      (set! run-streak 1)))
```

Persistence: winning multiple runs stacks bonuses. Dying resets.

## Variation 12 — Score attack (fixed session)

```scheme
;; Play for 3 minutes. Score all hits. No combo, no multiplier.
;; Just raw count.
(define (score-any-hit)
  (set! score (+ score 100)))
```

Simplest possible: rate * time = total. For pure-reflex practice
modes.

## Formulas with visual scaling

Display side. Bigger score = bigger text. Higher combo = larger
counter.

```scheme
(define (paint-score)
  (let ((size (min 24 (+ 12 (quotient combo 5)))))
    ;; Runtime doesn't have variable text size in the reference, so
    ;; scale via horizontal offset for prominence.
    (paint-text (string-append \"x\" (number->string combo))
                (- 300 (* 4 combo))
                (- 30 (min 20 combo)))))
```

## Display treatments — three grades of score-up feedback

### Understated
Just update the number. Fastest to render, easiest on brain.
Suitable for slow, contemplative games.

### Standard
Update number + 1-pixel camera shake. Enough to notice the hit.

### Explosive
Update number + camera shake proportional to hit value + audio ding
+ number briefly grows 20% before settling. Suitable for shmups,
rhythm games, high-arousal genres.

## Common desktop tasks

**Weekly-goal progress.** Shop owner sets a weekly sales goal. Each
sale = base score. Combo = 2× if within 5 minutes of previous. Total
displayed with mid-week celebration animations at 25%/50%/75%/100%.

**Support-response leaderboard.** Operator team scores: 1 point per
message answered, 2× combo if within 60 sec of receipt, 3× if
answered in shifts back-to-back. Rank displayed on team dashboard.

## The tuning rule

Score numbers should be memorable. Aim for a game where the top
score is a round number (10,000 or 100,000 or 1,000,000). Kids will
brag: 'I got 100k.' They don't brag: 'I got 87,431.' Round numbers
are memes.

Tune your base × combo × difficulty product to make round-number
targets ACHIEVABLE for average players and DIFFICULT to exceed.")
